g.text: ﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [1] In the beginning, God created the heavens and the earth.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [2] The earth was formless and empty. Darkness was on the surface of the deep and God’s Spirit was hovering over the surface of the waters.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [3] God said, “Let there be light,” and there was light.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [4] God saw the light, and saw that it was good. God divided the light from the darkness.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [5] God called the light “day”, and the darkness he called “night”. There was evening and there was morning, the first day.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [6] God said, “Let there be an expanse in the middle of the waters, and let it divide the waters from the waters.”
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [7] God made the expanse, and divided the waters which were under the expanse from the waters which were above the expanse; and it was so.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [8] God called the expanse “sky”. There was evening and there was morning, a second day.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [9] God said, “Let the waters under the sky be gathered together to one place, and let the dry land appear;” and it was so.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [10] God called the dry land “earth”, and the gathering together of the waters he called “seas”. God saw that it was good.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [11] God said, “Let the earth yield grass, herbs yielding seeds, and fruit trees bearing fruit after their kind, with their seeds in it, on the earth;” and it was so.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [12] The earth yielded grass, herbs yielding seed after their kind, and trees bearing fruit, with their seeds in it, after their kind; and God saw that it was good.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [13] There was evening and there was morning, a third day.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [14] God said, “Let there be lights in the expanse of the sky to divide the day from the night; and let them be for signs to mark seasons, days, and years;
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [15] and let them be for lights in the expanse of the sky to give light on the earth;” and it was so.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [16] God made the two great lights: the greater light to rule the day, and the lesser light to rule the night. He also made the stars.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [17] God set them in the expanse of the sky to give light to the earth,
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [18] and to rule over the day and over the night, and to divide the light from the darkness. God saw that it was good.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [19] There was evening and there was morning, a fourth day.
﻿Genesis. Chapter 1. [20] God said, “Let the waters abound with living creatures, and let birds fly above the earth in the open expanse of the sky.”
